Problem Statement: Concrete Strength Prediction¶

Author : Tulay Caglayan

Objective:¶

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file "concrete.csv". Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain a score above 85%.

Resources Available:¶

The data file "concrete.csv" is taken from olympus.greatlearning project page DataSet tab.
The data for this project is also available in file https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/concrete/compressive/.

Attribute Information:¶

Given are the variable name, variable type, the measurement unit, and a brief description. The concrete compressive strength is the regression problem. The order of this listing corresponds to the order of numerals along the rows of the database.

Independent Input Features :

1 - cement : Cement quantity by kg in m3 mixture  
2 - slag : Blast Furnace Slag quantity by kg in m3 mixture  
3 - ash : Fly Ash quantity by kg in m3 mixture
4 - water : Water quantity by kg in m3 mixture
5 - superplastic : Superplasticizer quantity by kg in m3 mixture
6 - coarseagg : Coarse Aggregate quantity by kg in m3 mixture
7 - fineagg : Fine Aggregate quantity by kg in m3 mixture
8 - age : Age by means of Day (1~365)

Dependent Output Feature(Target):

9 - strength : Concrete compressive strength in MPa

Steps to Follow¶

  1. Explore data
    • Explore data types
    • Find missing data and treat data
    • Find dublicates and treat if necessary
    • Find outliers and treat if necessary
    • Univariate analysis of the features to see distributions of the data
  2. Find correlation between features
    • Bivariate and multivariate analysis by drawing plots
    • Find correlation by using heapmap
  3. Make feature engineering.
    • Extract new features from existing features if any exists
    • Drop feature(s) if required
    • Get the data ready for model
    • Scale or normalize data if necessary
  4. Create and tune the models
    • Suitable models will be choosen after exploring data . We will understand what is nature of data, if it is regression or classification problem and so on. We can decide models to choose after explore.
    • Create, execute and tune the models
  5. Score and compare models
    • Models comparison will be done by using suitable scores.
    • KFold Cross Validation Score will be used before model hyperparameter tuning
    • After hyperparameter tuning, comparison will be made for the Test data scores which will be R squared(r2_score), mean_squared_error(MSE), mean_absolute_error(MAE) and root_mean_squared_error(RMSE)
  6. Choose best model
    • Best model will be choosen by considering score comparisons.
  7. Business Conclusion
    • Business meaning will be discussed and advices will be given

Content¶

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis
  2. Bivariate Analysis
  3. Feature Engineering Techniques
  4. Creating and Tuning Model
  5. Significance of R2 Score
  6. Recommendations for Business

Explore Outliers¶

An outlier is an observation that is unlike the other observations. Outliers can have many causes, such as:

  • Measurement or input error.
  • Data corruption.
  • True outlier observation

Since our data is not Gaussian distributed , we will use IQR(InterQuartile Range) for describing outliers. The IQR is calculated as the difference between the 75th and the 25th percentiles of the data

The IQR can be used to identify outliers by defining limits on the sample values that are 1.5 times of the IQR below the 25th percentile or above the 75th percentile

In [11]:
# Identify Outliers using IQR
def outliers_by_IQR(df): 
    
    iqr_list ={}
    
    for col in df.columns : 
        # calculate interquartile range
        q25, q50, q75 = np.percentile(df[col], 25),np.percentile(df[col], 50), np.percentile(df[col], 75)
        iqr = q75 - q25

        # calculate the outlier cutoff
        cut_off = iqr * 1.5
        lower, upper = q25 - cut_off, q75 + cut_off

        # identify outliers
        outliers = [x for x in df[col] if x < lower or x > upper]
        
        # Outliers percentage of data by IQR
        perc_by_IQR = 100 * len(outliers)/ len(df[col])

        # Count of Outliers
        count_outliers = len(outliers) 
        
        # Distinct Outlier values
        outlier_set = ''
        if outliers: 
            outlier_set = sorted(set(outliers))
        
        iqr_list[col] = { 'Min_Whisker' : lower,
                          '%25' : q25,
                          '%50' : q50,
                          '%75' : q75,
                          'Max_Whisker' : upper,
                          'IQR' : iqr,
                          'Outlier_Count' : count_outliers,
                          '%Outlier_by_IQR' : '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(perc_by_IQR,2)) , 
                          'Distinct_Outlier_Values' : outlier_set
                        }
    df_result = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(iqr_list, orient='index')
    df_result = df_result \
                 .sort_values(by=['%Outlier_by_IQR'], ascending=False) \
                 .style.apply(lambda x:['background: lightgreen' if x.name == '%Outlier_by_IQR' else '' for i in x], axis=0)
    return df_result
    
# Print Outlier percentages by IQR 
outliers_by_IQR(df)

q1 = 23.71
q3 = 46.14

fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=2, nrows=4, figsize=[14, 16])

for ax, col in zip(np.ravel(axes), features) :
    sns.distplot(df[ (df["strength"] < q1)][col], color='red', label='<= '+str(q1) ,rug=True, ax=ax )
    sns.distplot(df[ (df["strength"] >= q1) & (df["strength"] <= q3)][col], color='b', label=str(q1)+' - '+str(q3) ,rug=True, ax=ax )
    sns.distplot(df[ (df["strength"] > q3) ][col], color='green', label='> '+str(q3) ,rug=True, ax=ax )
    ax.legend()
    ax.set_title(col.capitalize() +" Density for Strength Levels")
    
plt.show()

  • There is no effect of slag and ash on strength
  • There is negative effect of water on strength. More water decreases strength and less water increases strength
  • There is slight effect of superplastic on strength. More superplastic leads to more strength , less superplastic less strength
  • We can say there is no effect of fineagg and coarseagg on strength, since effect is too small that it can be ignored
  • The older the mixture, the more strengther it is . Mixture with less age is weaker
  • There are zero values for slag, ash and superplastic

Derive New Features and Drop If Required¶

I tried models with new features. But either they overfitted for train data or R2 Score performance is decreased for test data.

I tried by dropping features. After I executed my models, models' test performances went down.

I tried polynomial Features and tested on models . Model performances went down. So, I returned back

Details are as below

Define Function¶

This function will be used after each feature add and each feature drop. Function will fit model, score model and save results. Later on, results will be compared to decide for adding or dropping features

In [20]:
# I chosed XGBoost to try since at last XGBoost is my best model
# I try to improve performance by adding new features or dropping  current features

# set model object to test for features
model_feature_test = XGBRegressor(learning_rate=0.15,n_estimators=350, max_depth=5,verbosity=0)

# set scaler object
scaler = StandardScaler()

# initialize scores dictionary
feature_scores = {}
    
def feature_test(X, y, name, imp_flag=0):
    
    # split data 
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.3, random_state=7)

    # scale
    X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

    # fit 
    model_feature_test.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # scores
    train_score = model_feature_test.score(X_train, y_train)
    test_score = model_feature_test.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    new_feature_importance = ''
    if imp_flag == 1:
        new_feature_importance = model_feature_test.feature_importances_[-1]
    
    # save result 
    feature_scores[name] = [train_score,test_score, new_feature_importance]

independent_features = df_new.drop('strength',axis=1).columns 

# ***** try with new feature by pairs ****
for f1 in independent_features: # We search for the pair which will increase the performance of the model
    for f2 in independent_features:
        
        if ((f1 != f2 ) and 
           ((f1 + '_' + f2) not in feature_scores) and
           ((f2 + '_' + f1) not in feature_scores)):
            
            X = df_new[independent_features]
            y = df_new['strength']

            # add new feature 
            new_feature_name = f1 + '_' + f2
            # instead of multiply, plus results were better
            X[new_feature_name] =  X[f1] + X[f2]

            # Fit data on model and save score
            feature_test(X, y, new_feature_name, 1)

  • By adding new feature pairs descreases performance of model on Test data. 3 of them slightly seems better on test data than original data. But not big difference.   • By DROPPING fineagg, ash, slag, performance of model on Test data decreased.
  • Dropping coarseagg increased Test score. I will drop "coarseagg" feature
  • Best result is for "DROP FEATURE coarseagg"
  • As a result, I will add new feature "ash_superplastic". I will drop feature "coarseagg" and go on with new data

Decide on the complexity of the model¶

  • Model will be regression model since this is a regresion problem having continues target values . Target does not have categorical values
  • Model cannot be Linear Regression model since there is no linear relation between data
  • We will work with following algorithms:
    • Decision Tree,
    • Ensemble models such as;
      • Random Forest
      • Bagging,
      • Boosting,
        • GradientBoostingRegressor: I will use this boosting model
        • XGBRegressor : I will use this boosting model
        • LGBMRegressor : Light GBM is sensitive to overfitting and can easily overfit small data. I don't prefer to use since our data is small
        • AdaBoostRegressor: Performs worse when irrelevant features are included. In our case, since features are irrevalent(no correlation), we expect this model to be worst . So I won't try this model
    • SVM: Support Vector Machine. SVR algorithm will be used from SVM modul

4. Creating and Tuning Model

This session will include work for model creation and tuning:

  • Suitable algorithms will be choosen for the project. At least 3 algorithms, one bagging and one boosting based algorithms wil be used and accuracy on testing set will be performed for 90% accuracy

  • Kfold Cross-Validation will be used to evaluate model performance.

  • Appropriate metrics will be use to compare models

  • Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit. Instead of Grid Search, Random Searchwill be used since Random Search performance is better than Grid Search

  • After hyperparameter tuning and models metrics will be compared by using DataFrame

Regression algorithms may be used are :

Bagging Models :

  • RandomForestRegressor : Ensemble model made of many decision trees using bootstrapping, random subsets of features, and average voting to make predictions.
  • BaggingRegressor : (Bootstrap Aggregation) Bagging in ensemble machine learning takes several weak models, aggregating the predictions to select the best prediction. When base_estimator parameter is not set, the base estimator is set to DecisionTreeRegressor

Boosting Models :

  • GradientBoostingRegressor : Supervised machine learning technique which produces a prediction model in the form of an ensemble of weak prediction models, typically decision trees.
  • XGBRegressor : XGBoost is an implementation of gradient boosted decision trees designed for speed and performance

  • LGBMRegressor: Light GBM is a gradient boosting framework that uses tree based learning algorithm. Light GBM grows tree vertically while other algorithm grows trees horizontally. It is not advisable to use LGBM on small datasets. Light GBM is sensitive to overfitting and can easily overfit small data. I don't prefer to use since our data is small

  • AdaBoostRegressor:(Adaptive Boosting) performs worse when irrelevant features are included. In our case , since features are irrevalent, we expect this model to be worst . So I won't try this model

DecisionTree:

  • DecisionTreeRegressor: Model breaks down a dataset into smaller and smaller subsets while at the same time an associated decision tree is incrementally developed. The final result is a tree with decision nodes and leaf nodes.

SVM Model

  • SVR : Epsilon-Support Vector Regression

Note: Our choosen models are not sensitive to outliers

Metrics and Scoring¶

Before tuning, cross_valudation_score will be used to choose models.

After tune models, since problem is regression problem, metrics on Test data will be used from sklearn.metrics module are:

  • R Square : : R Square measures how much of variability in dependent variable can be explained by the model. It is square of Correlation Coefficient(R). R Square is calculated by the sum of squared of prediction error divided by the total sum of square which replace the calculated prediction with mean. Best possible score is 1.0 and it can be negative in case the model is arbitrarily worse
  • Mean squared error(MSE) : While R Square is a relative measure of how well the model fits dependent variables, Mean Square Error is an absolute measure of the goodness for the fit. MSE is calculated by the sum of square of prediction error which is real output minus predicted output and then divide by the number of data points
  • Root Mean Square Error(RMSE): Root Mean Square Error(RMSE) is the square root of MSE. It is used more commonly than MSE because firstly sometimes MSE value can be too big to compare easily. Secondly, MSE is calculated by the square of error, and thus square root brings it back to the same level of prediction error and make it easier for interpretation.
  • Mean absolute error(MAE) : Mean Absolute Error(MAE) is similar to Mean Square Error(MSE). However, instead of the sum of square of error in MSE, MAE is taking the sum of absolute value of error.Compare to MSE or RMSE, MAE is a more direct representation of sum of error terms. MSE gives larger penalisation to big prediction error by square it while MAE treats all errors the same.

Metrics Function¶

Reporting function will do following :

  • Calculate r2-score and other metrics
  • Store each metric for models in dictionary in order to compare results as dataframe
In [30]:
# report_model function will be used to draw report for models and 
# to store each metric for models in order to compare results

tuned_model_metrics = {} 

def save_metrics(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test,  model_name, model):
    
    y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)    
    
    
    # Save metrics
    tuned_model_metrics[model_name] = {
             'MAE(Train)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred_train),2)),
             'MAE(Test)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_test),2)),
             'MSE(Train)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train),2)),
             'MSE(Test)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test),2)),
             'RMSE(Train)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train)),2)),
             'RMSE(Test)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test)),2)),
             'R2-Score(Train)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(r2_score(y_train, y_pred_train),2)),
             'R2-Score(Test)': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(r2_score(y_test, y_pred_test),2))
            }
        
        
## Save Cross validation results 
cross_val_scores = {}

def save_cross_val_score(scores, model_name):
    # Save cv score
    cross_val_scores[model_name] = {
             'cross_val_score mean': '{:.2f}'.format(np.round(np.mean(scores),2)),
             'cross_val_scores': '{}'.format(scores)
            }

Tune Models¶

  • For hyperparameter tuning, GridSearchCV and(or) RandomizedSearchCV will be used

  • What is Hyper Parameter? : Model configuration argument specified by the developer to guide the learning process for a specific dataset. Hyperparameters are different from parameters. Parameters are learned automatically from data; hyperparameters are set manually to help guide the learning process

  • What is Hyper Parameter Tuning? : It is often required to search for a set of hyperparameters that result in the best performance of a model on a dataset. This is called hyperparameter optimization, hyperparameter tuning

  • What is Grid Search :Every combination of a preset list of values of the hyper-parameters is tried and the model is evaluated for each combination.

  • What is Randomized Search? : Random combination of predefined bounded domain of the hyper-parameters is tried and the model is evaluated for each combination.

  • GridSearchCV vs RandomizedSearchCV : Grid search is appropriate for small and quick searches of hyperparameter values that are known to perform well generally. Random search is appropriate for discovering new hyperparameter values or new combinations of hyperparameters. Random Search usually gives better performance and does not try all combinations of hyperparameters.

Decision Tree¶

In [41]:
# Decision Tree

# Possible parameters to set :
# max_leaf_nodes : Best nodes are defined as relative reduction in impurity. If None then unlimited number of leaf nodes
# criterion{“mse”, “friedman_mse”, “mae”, “poisson”}: The function to measure the quality of a split. 
#            Supported criteria are “mse” for the mean squared error, which is equal to variance reduction as feature selection 
#            criterion and minimizes the L2 loss using the mean of each terminal node, “friedman_mse”, which uses mean squared 
#            error with Friedman’s improvement score for potential splits, “mae” for the mean absolute error, which minimizes 
#            the L1 loss using the median of each terminal node, and “poisson” which uses reduction in Poisson deviance 
#            to find splits.
# max_depth: maximum depth of the tree. If None, nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all 
#            leaves contain less than min_samples_split samples.

param_grid = {'max_leaf_nodes':  [10,100,200], 
              'criterion': ['mse', 'mae','poisson'],
              'max_depth': [5,8,10,12]
             }

# n_splits : Number of splitting iterations.
kfold = KFold(n_splits=KFOLD, random_state=RANDOM_STATE)

# create model 
model_dt = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeRegressor(), param_grid, cv=kfold, scoring='r2') 

# fit model with train data 
model_dt.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Save metrics and scores of the model
save_metrics(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test,  'Decison Tree', model_dt)

# print best hyper parameters
print("Best hyper parameters: %s" % model_dt.best_params_)

Best hyper parameters: {'criterion': 'mae', 'max_depth': 12, 'max_leaf_nodes': 200}

             }

kfold = KFold(n_splits=KFOLD, random_state=RANDOM_STATE)

# create model 
model_svm = RandomizedSearchCV(SVR(verbose=False), param_grid, cv=kfold, scoring='r2') 

# fit model with train data 
model_svm.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Save metrics and scores of the model
save_metrics(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test,  'SVM', model_svm)

# print best hyper parameters
print("Best hyper parameters: %s" % model_svm.best_params_)

Best hyper parameters: {'C': 6, 'degree': 4, 'epsilon': 1.0530791131619324, 'gamma': 'auto', 'kernel': 'rbf'}

5. Significance of R2 Score

R2 Score is better used to explain the model to business people, because we can explain score as a percentage of the output variable.
For example, r-squared of 90% reveals that 90% of the data fits the regression model. Higher r-squared indicates a better fit for the model.

Before explain the effect of an increase/decrease in the R2 score on the business model, let's investigate formula:

R2_Score = 1 - (SS_Regression/ SS_Total)
R2_Score = 1 - (sum( y - y_predicted )^2 / sum( y - y_mean )^2)







R2 Score is best for value 1 : That means model predicted all actual values correctly. If for all data y_actual = y_predicted, then denominator(SS Regression) will be 0 . 1- 0 = 1 is the best score.

R2 Score can take 0 value: If model predicts output variable as expected value of y (mean) for every input data, denominator(SS Regression) will be equal to nominator(SS Total). Then, model will get R2 Score of 0.

R2 Score can take negative values.: When denominator(SS Regression) > nominator(SS Total) , value will be bigger than 1. 1- (value bigger than 1) will have negative value. That means model predicts very bad. Model cannot predict actual values correctly , model even did not predict the expected mean value.

As conclusion for increase and decrease in R2 score, increase on R2 means that the business model predicts better for actual values, decrease on R2 means that the business model predicts worse for actual values

6. Recommendations for Business

As a conclusion, recommendations which may be beneficial to the business based on the whole analysis will be written with reasons.

  • Cement is the most important features for mixture. Use more cement to make mixture stronger. Cement increases the strength of the mixture
  • Age is the second important feature for mixture. Mixture is more stronger if you wait more days. The older the mixture the stronger it is.
  • Use less water in mixture, since more water effects strength of mixture in a negative way and decreases the strength of the mixture
  • Slag, ash, superplastics are not too much effect on strength. You don't have to use them in your mixture. They are not must, nice to have. If you use superplastics, it effects strengthness slightly in a positive way
  • Effect of fineagg and coarseagg on strength are small. Despide that, use less fineagg and coarseagg to make mixture stronger, since they have slightly negative effect on the strength of the mixture
